 have 5 slots, say<br>0 0 0 2 0<br><br>and then you have to &quot;push&quot; the 2 like<br>0 0 0 0 2<br><br>at the end it gets popped off<br>0 0 0 0 0<br><br>I actually had to do this exact program last semester in school, but I can't find my notebook with it =( I'll keep looking.  You're going to need an array dimmed with 5 slots (as said above)<br><br>A sample class might be (and if this is off, someone please correct me, it's been awhile)<br><br>Class Queue<br>  Public:<br>  Queue(); // Constructor<br>  int getnewnum() // have this ask the user for a new number to put in the que (if that's how it's supposed to be done)<br>  void pushnum(int que[5]) // this function will move all of the numbers up a slot, pop the last number, and add the new number.<br>  Private:<br>  int somenum, que[5];<br>The code would look something like this, but this won't work by itself.<br><br>Queue::Queue()  <br>{<br> int somenum, que[ 5 ];  // Initialize variables<br> somenum = 0;<br> for (int x = 0, x &lt; 5, x++)<br>   { que[x]=0; }  <br> return;<br>}<br><br>int Queue::Getnewnum() // get number from user<br>{ cin &gt;&gt; somenum<br>   return somenum;<br>}<br><br>void Queue::Pushnum(int que[ 5 ])<br>{<br> cout &lt;&lt; que[4] &lt;&lt; &quot; is no longer in the que!&quot;;  // prepare to pop!<br> for (int y = 4; y &gt; 1; y--)<br> {<br>  que[y] = que[y-1]; // Move all numbers up one slot.<br> }<br>  que[ 0 ] = somenum;  // Insert new number<br>  cout &lt;&lt; que[ 0 ] &lt;&lt; &quot; has been added to the que!&quot;; <br>}<br><br>-------<br><br>That's most of it, might need some tweaking, as I didn't test it.  Hopefully that helps =) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uaillaandarkforge.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aillaan Darkforge</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span